{"/service/ndnp/khi/batch_khi_arbuckle_ver02/data/sn82016014/00212474150/1920101801/0187.xml":{"full_text":"THE TOPEKA DAILY STATE JOURNAIA-MONDAY EVENING, OCTOBER 18, 1920\n-4\nAft Independent Kcm pep\nBY FUANK P. MAC LENNAS\nj\nVOLUME XL.II.\nNo. 244\nEntered as rond claas matter.\nOFFICIAL CITY PAPEK OB\" IOKKA.\nSubscription Bates by Mail.\nJlv mall In advance, one r. IJJ.00\niiy lnoil ia adranue, aix niontlia... S.0O\nlty innll In advance, turee inentlis. 1.50\nhy wall hi advance, ona mouth... .00\nRata by Carrier.\nOna week J\"\nOne moutli 05 eeuta\nTelephone 3530.\nfcaatoru oKii-e: Paul Block, representa\ntive. fo. ti3 Madison avauue. New lork.\nCentury building thk-afO Little Bldg.,\nilVio\"; Knvse building. Detroit; Lewie\nllldtf., liuuaiu\nNewspaper Publlshera' Association, Audit\nMKMUKK OF THK AbbOCIATED PBKSS.\nTlie Associated Tress is exclusively tn-tltlr-d\nt, the ..sa Ut publication\nuewallapatc-he credited to It If not other-\nixVrciited In tliis paper and also tne\nfle news lubimncu uercm,\nINFORMATION FOR .ALL READERS W\nTHE TOPEKA STATE JOURNAL.\nEach reader of Tbe State Journal U of\nfered the unlimited uae ot tbe largeat in\ntorroatlon bureau In tba world.\nThis Service Bureau la located tbe\nnational capital, where It la In Immediate\ntouch with all tbe great leaources ot the\nUnited States government.\nIt can answer practically any nutation\nyou want to ask, but it can t give d-vii-p,\nor make exbaostlve research.\nThe war forced so many changes In tbe\ndally life of the American people that the\nservice of this :nformstlon bureau will Is\nInvaluable to all who use It.\nKeep la touch with your goTernsnent St\nall times. It can help jpu In a tboueana\nwars if yonr waiits are only made known.\nThe State Journal pays for this splendid\nservice In order that every one of Its\nreaders may take free advantage or It.\nYou are welcome to use It aa often aa joa\nlike\nWrite yonr request briefly, sign yonr\nname and addresi plainly, enclose a 2-cent\natamn for return postage and address, tne\nTOTSka STATE JOUllNAL 1NFOEMA\nTION BUREAU.\nFrederic J. Haskln, Director, Washing\nton, D. C.\nThe Topeka house building; organi\nzation Is reported to be planning; a\ncampaign for Increasing; Its member\nship. What the concern needs most\nand should go after is money to\nfinance a building program. A aim\nliar Institution In North Topeka is do\ning business rlgbt along and' finding a\nmarket for its houses as fast as It\nbuilds them. Ono trouble With many\nenterprises is that they are so slow\nin getting into operation that the need\nfor them .has disappeared before they\nbegin to function.\nSenator Penrose is quoted as saying\nthat he has discovered much opposi\ntion to a tax on sales. Its opponents\nprobably are those who have failed\nto find any way of dodging it or pass\ning it on. Many personi think that If\nPenrose opposes a measure the thing\nmust be all right.\nIt is reported that an aeroplane\nsystem of transportation will be es\ntablished between Key West and Ha\nvana in November. The ships wiJJ\nrarry eleven passengers each and are\nexpected to carry the mails and to\nmake the trip of ninety miles in about\nan hour. This will enable residents\nof Key West to fly over and get a\ndrink before breakfast.\nThe fall in the price of raw cotton\nsnems to be making rapid progress in\nthe direction of the consumer but\nthere is; little indication ot a similar\ntrend In hoga, cattle and grain.\nFood, it is declared, is now leading\nall other necessities in the downward\nsweep of prices, but patrons of Topeka\neating houses would never suspect it.\nGovernor Cox took the stump early\nin the campaign. Senator Harding\nfinally has abandoned the front porch\nand gone out to the people, but Debs\ncontinues to carry on his campaign\nfrom within the walls of his tempor\nary abode in Atlanta.\nDr. Charles W. Eliot defines \"Amer\nica first\" as meaning, in respect to\nnational conduct, not moral leader\nship and enterprise, and service with\nout thought ot Belt, but selfishness,\ndesertion of brave comrades-in-arms,\nseeking cover from new risks for lib\nerty and humanity, and refusal to par\nticipate in protecting the weak against\nthe strong, and in making aggressive\nwar too dangerous, in either civilized\nor barbarous regions, to be under\ntaken.\nSenator Harding in his Des Moinss\nspeech said: \"I do not want any one\nto be misled. I will have no man's\nvote upon a misunderstanding, and I\nam equally determined, if I can pre\nvent it, that my opponent shall have\nno man'svote upon a misunderstand\ning.\" Yet there are extant two ver\nsions pf his position on the League of\nNations. The senator should take\npains to set Mr. Taft and Mr. Hoover\nright. Mr. Harding is reported to\nhave said further: \"I do not want to\nclarify these obligations (in the\nleagued: I want to turn my back upon\nthem. It is not interpretation but re\njection that I am seeking.\" And those\nv.-ho favor the covenant for peace. It\nis reported, were bidden by Senator\nHarding to vote for the Democrat\nticker.\nIn the general slump In prices carry\ning with It losses in almost every line\n\"ff business, the farmer feels that he\nis carrying the heavy end of the bur\nden. Attention has boen called time\nand again in this paper to the fact that\na fall in prices would bring serious\ndisturbance, to business and wide\nspread financial loss. .Declines in\nprices come high but we must have\nthem and few can escape their con\nsequences. If it be any consolation to\nthe producer of food, he can reflect\nthat about everybody else is or will be\nin the same boat.\nMOTOR TRANSPORTATION.\nThe recent advance In railroad\nfreight rates is developing a type ot\ncompetition which only a generally in\ncreasing and over-capacity business\nwill prevent from being severely, dan\ngerous to railroad earnings. Motor\ntransportation on the public high\nways, both .passenger and freight, is\nbeing developed in uoh a -way as to\ncause apprehension on the part of\nrailroad companies, and in many In\nstances to enlist very active opposi\ntion. This is manifest in the efforts\nwhich are being made 'to prevent the\nuse of the roadways for motor-truck\ntransportation except upon payment of\nsuch charge for the use of the road\nways as will prevent motor transpor\ntation from remaining, a competitive\nfactor. It is urged that the upkeep\nof the public highways is born by\ngeneral taxations while railroad com\npanies are not onry forced to maintain\ntheir own rails, but aIsoto assist in the\nmaintenance of the highways thru tax\nation.\nIt may be noted in this connection,\nhowever, that the railroads are col\nlecting the money necessary to pay\nthese taxes from the people and are\ngranted power by the government to\ncontinue to do so and earn 6 per cent\non their Investment beside. The\ntruckers are asking no favors from\nanybody.\nA tiro company in Akron, Ohio, for\nmany months during the) war and con\ntinuously to the present lime, has\ntransported its product from its fac\ntory to Boston, Mass., by motor truck\nbecause its deliveries are more quick\nly made and the cost practically the\nsame.\nThere canbe no question, says the\nMining Congress Journal,, that the\nhaulage of freight over steel rails upon\nsteel wheels and with ordinary train\ncrews should be made at a much lower\ncost than would be possible over as\nphalt roads and upon rubber tires with\nthe required man-power many times\nmultiplied. Where a long haul' can\nbe made more quickly by -motor truck\nthan by rail there is something radi\ncally wrong with the railroad) service.\nWhere a short haul can be made more\ncheaply by motor than by railroad\nthere is something absolutely wrong\nwith the railroad freight rates.\nWhen motor truck freight transpor\ntation over any considerable distance\nis at all possible in competition with\nrailroad transportation it is proof thatLdrlve the repeal bill thru congress.\nthe railway service is so clumsily han\ndled as to need such competition in\norder that it shall be made more effi\nciently to meet the public require\nments. RAILROADS COMIKG BACK.\n3AD8\nOne of the notable' evidences that\nthe country ia getting back to normal\nmay;, be seen In the fact that the rail\nroads are no longer merely accepting\nsuch business as is offered, but they\nare actively soliciting passenger traf\nfic and freight accounts. This hus\ntling for new business comes strikingly\nhome to delegates to any large con\nvention who find in their mall several\nletters from competing lines suggest\ning that -this or that railroad Is\nequipped to furnish service unsur\npassed by Its rivals. The freight so\nlicitor, almost an extinct functionary\nIn the last few years, has again made\nhis appearance and he is trying to see\nto it that his promises In reference to\ncars and service are made good by the\noperating department.\nEconomies are being installed wher\never they do net Interfere wfth effi\nciency. This policy is most striking\nly evidenced in the repair of old equip\nment, which, under the government\nregime, was sidetracked or Junked.\nThe road have made the most of their\nopportunities in this respect, and thou\nsands of earl out of commission a few\nmonths ago have been put back into\nservice.\nIndifferent or inefficient employes\nare being weeded out. This is greatly\nto the interest of the traveling and\nshipping, public, as the best men are\nbeing-retained. Pay rolls are being\nreduced without any reduction In serv\nice. The most striking feature, says the\nWollman Review, ia the improved\nmorale of the operating department.\nIntensive methods have been adopted\nfor speeding up traffic, and the goal\nset by the Association of Railway Ex\necutives is thirty miles per car per\nday. This would be equal to an in\ncrease in equipment of several hun\ndred thousand cars. This question has\nbeen' given the most careful and sys\ntematic study. Efforts have been\nmade to obtain the co-operation of the\nshipping public, as it Is realized that\nthe railroads cannot function 100 per\ncent without this aid. Solid trains are\nbeing organised for one destination,\nand it is believed that this method can\nbe improved greatly by carefully\nanalyzing the freight for movement\nat a given point. Accumulations are\nbeing avoided by the use of embar\ngoes and permits. Idle freight cars\nare being eliminated as much as pos\nalble. Refrigerator cars when not\nneeded for service requiring refriger\nation are dried out and used for load\ning merchandise and other freight.\nThe railroad statistics are beginning to\nshow that these efforts are meeting\nwith success.\nThos far private operation is mak\ning good. The Investor is pleased by\nthe record of economy and efficiency,\nand the public is pleased by the im\nprovement in service which makes for\nIts conveniens tn traveling and for an\nImprovement tin the conduct ot busi\nness. y\nThe sugar crop of Cuba which' was\nbeing held at 24 cents a pound now\nIs available to purchasers at 1 cents.\nThe old law of supply and demand Is\nback on the job.\nTOPEKA STATE JOURNAL\nInformation Bureau\nFREDERIC J. BASKET, DtaectOR-4\nWashington, D. C\nPRESIDEXTIAIi CAMPAIGN'S.\nThe McKlnley-Bryan Race of 1806.\nWashington, Oct. 15. -The hardest\nfought political battle of American\nhistory was the campaign of 1S96 in\nwhich William McKinley t Ohio, van\nquished William Jennings Bryan of\nNebraska. The \"fact that McKinley\nwas, re-elected with ease In his second\ncampaign against Bryan, and that the\nRepublican majorities of 1896 look\nso great on paper, has caused many\nmen of short memory to believe that\nMcKinley won his first electidn with\nout great difficulty.\nIn that year the Democratic nomi\nnee, Mr. Bryan, made the most re\nmarkable speaking campaign' ever un\ndertaken by any man. In the BMtie\nyear, the Republican campaign- man\nager, Mr. Hanna, spent five times as\nmuch money as had ever been spent\nbefore in a presidential race. The He\npublican campaign was conducted\nwith such consummate skill that the\nname of Mark Hanna will live for\nyeara as that of the best political\ngeneral the country has produced.\nThe year 1896-was a year of politi\ncal revolution. Both of the leading\nparties underwent great changes, and\nthe number of independent voters was\nIncreased a thousand fold. Mr. Cleve\nland's second administration began\nwith the country on the verge of a fi\nnancial crash. The blow descended\nand the panic of 1S93 was on. The\nmoney question, which both parties\nhad so carefully side-stepped for so\nmany years was presented in such a\nway that the administration could not\navoid taking a position. Mr. Cleve\nland and his cabinet decided to place\nthe country squarely on the gold\nstandard, and to disregard the petty\nsops which had been thrown to sliver.\nThe treasury regulations accomplished\ntheir purpose long before the Mc\nKinley administration came in.\nDemocrats in Control.\nFor the first time since the first\npart of Buchanan's administration the\ngovernment was in the control of the\nDemocrats, that party having-the pres\nident and a majority in both houses\nof congress. Mr. Cleveland called\ncongress together and urged the re\npeal of the silver purchasing clause of\nthe Sherman Act, which would finally\n\"demonetize\" silver. His party dla not\nagree with him on that subject, and it\nwas with the greatest difficulty that\nhis purpose was accomplished.\nPresident Cleveland had been an\nexemplar of civil service reform, and\nwas opposed to \"pernicious activity\"\nin politics, but he went to the extreme\nof the use of oatronage as a club to\nEven then, it was done only by the\nhelp of eastern Republican votes. It\nleft his party hopelessly divided.\nThe Democratic landslide which re\nelected Cleveland was the result of\npopular disapproval of the McKinley\ntariff bill of 1890. After the terrific\nfight on the silver purchasing clause\nrepeal, the Democratic congress en\ndeavored to enact a Democratic tariff\nbill. The party was already torn\nasunder and could act with no una\nnimity. The result was the passage of\nHie Wilson bill, which Mr. cieveiana\npermitted to become a law without\nhis signature.\nAs the people had condemned the\nMcKinley bill six months after it was\npassed and before its effect could pos\nsibly have been felt, by the election\nof the Democratic house in 1890, so\nthe Wilson bill, charged with responsi\nbility for a panic which was on be\nfore the bill was written, resulted in\nthe overwhelming Republican con\ngressional victory of 1894.\nA Year of Split Parties.\nAll thru the three years e rfce Cleve\nland administration leading up to cam\npaign of 189 there was strife in both\nparties. For a time it seemea tnat tne\nRepublicans would declare for free sil\nver and that the Democrats would fol\nlow their president in advocacy for the\ngold standard. Then It seemea tnat\nboth parties would declare for the\ngold standard and the sir hosts\nw-quld enroll under the banner of\nPopulism. The Republicans felt cer\ntain that they could win on the pros\nperity issue, and by denouncing the\nCleveland administration for its issue\nof 362,000,000 of bonds In \"time of\nprofound peace.\" But they didn't\nwant to split their own forces by tak\ning sides in the money fight.\nMr. McKinley and Speaker Thomas\nB. Reed were the leading candidates\nfor the Republican nomination for\npresident. Mr. McKinley had the good\nfortune to have Mark Hanna for his\npolitical captain. Hanna organized\nthe states and took even New England\naway from Reed long before the con\nvention met. Mr. Hanna was afraid of\nthe- money question and Mr. McKinley\nwas committed by his record to \"bi\nmetallism.\" So the Ohio leaders at\ntempted to \"straddle\" the issue once\nmore. The Qhio state platform con\ntained a delphic utterance on the\nmoney question which said nothing.\nBut when the national convention\nmet at St. Louis Mr. Hanna found\nthat the question was one which was\ntoo big to be straddled. Senator\nThomas C. Piatt of New York forced\nHanna to accept a gold standard plat\nform. It was later modified by a\npronouncement In favor of interna\ntional bimetallism, which permitted\nRepublicans who had been shouting\nfor silver to come down gracefully.\nSenator Piatt may not be regarded as\na great statesman, but In 1898 and\n1900 he did things that left marks on\nthe history of the country.\nWesterners Bolted. S\nWhen the gold plank was adopted,\nthirty-four western Republican dele\ngates. Headed by Senator Teller of\nColorado, Senator Oannon of Utah,\nand Senator Dubois of Idaho, walked\nout of the convention and into the\nDemocratic party. All over the\ncountry there were Republicans who\nloudly proclaimed the fact that they\nhad bolted the nomination of McKin\nley. A national silver Republican\nconvention was called. Mr. Hanna,\nChosen chairman of the national com\nmittee, knew that he had a great job\nahead of him and he set to work.\nThe Democratic convention met in\nChicago. The Cleveland wing of the\nparty controlled the national commit\ntee, but the recommendations of that\nbody were swept aside on the first\nvote and it was clear that the silver\nmen controlled the convention. A res\nolution commending' the then present\nDemocratic convention was voted\ndown with vengeful hoots. No man\nwas ever hated more than the Demo\ncratic national convention of 1S9C\nhated Grover Cleveland the Demo\ncratic president of the United States.\nLeading free silver advocates like\nRichard P Bland of Missouri and\nJohn R. McLean of Ohio w-ere contest\ning for the nomination. The story of\ntheir defeat is a most familiar it of\npolitical history. William Jennings\nBryan, who had reported the St. Louis\nconvention which nominated McKin\nley, for a Nebraska newspaper, came\nto Chicago at the head of a, contesting\ndelegation. He was given a seat.\nThen came the great debate on the\nplatform, the eastern Democrats fight\ning hard against the majority. In that\ndebate, Mr. Bryan, then only tt years\nold, slim of figure and full of mane,\nleaped into world-wide fame in a mo\nment.. The famous \"crown of thorns\nand cross of gold\" speech, whether the\nfigure was borrowed from Representa\ntive McCall of Massachusetts or not,\nsent that convention wild., Bryan was\nnominated.\nTriumph of the Boy Orator.\nA little later the Populists and the\nSilver Republicans \"also nominated\n\"the Boy Orator of the Platte.\" The\nCleveland Democrats' called a con\nvention at Indianapolis and organized\nthe \"National Democracy.\" Gen, John\nM. Palmer of Illinois, a soldier of the\nUnion, was nominated tor president,\nwith Gen. Simon Bolivar Buckner of\nKentucky, a soldier of the Confed\neracy, for vice president. They polled\nbiH few votes, the majority of the gold\nDemocrats voting straight for McKin\nley. Bryan soon began his unprecedented\nand unequalled campaign tour. He did\nnot then .possess the suavity of his\nlater years, but he was mightily in\nearnest. No other man has ever\naroused the enthusiasm which he cre\nated in that campaign. He spoke to\nover five million people, making over\na thousand separate speeches. In the\nfirst part of the campaign he traveled\nin ordinary day coaches, the railroads\nmaking it as hard for-him as possible.\nToward the end of the campaign the\nrailroads relented and he was enabled\nto get a private car. He was without\nmoney and in his great canvass was\nsometimes forced ,to borrow the price\nof a ticket to the next stopping place.\nAgainst this terrific campaign,\nwhich seemed to be sweeping the\ncountry for the Democrats, Mr. Hanna\nplanned the great \"campaign of edu\ncation.\" The farmers of the agricul\ntural states east of the Mississippi\nwere induced to believe that- the elec\ntion of Bryan would mean bankruptcy\nfor them. All of the wealth of the\ncountry was back of Hanna he had\nmillions to spend and he knew how to\ndo it.\nCareful canvasses taken two months\nbefore the election showed that such\nstates as Ohio and Indiana were for\nBryan. The work that was .done to\nturn that defeat into the overwhelm\ning victory of November was due to\nthe political sagacity of Marcus A\nHanna. Bryan's appeals to the .people of\nevery section, the enormous popular\nInterest in his personality and the pic\nturesqueness of his campaign, on the\none side, and the efforts of the \"\"Re\npublicans to reach every voter with\ncampaign literature and personal argu\nment on the other side, resulted in a\nwidespread popular interest in politics\nsuch as had never been known.\nWhile the campaign was decisive,\nand while it practically settled the\nmoney question for all time, defeat\ndid not diminish the popularity of the\nDemocratic standard-bearer, who has\never since stood high in the councils\nof his party. McKinley was chosen\npresident and his administration wit\nnessed the return of prosperity, the\ngreatest the country has ever known.\nAfter all, not the least among the Re.\nr, M j. i,b,iuj .A V J w s o nil. mean\npublican assets of 1896 .was the factlou vant gugar on your bread and\nthat the panic of 1893 came during a\nDemocratic administration.\nQuestions Answers\nQ. \"What Is the mennine of the- picture\n\"Hope,\" showing blindfolded tvomaa sit\nting on globe C. K.\nA. It ia aald that George Frederic\nWatts, the oa inter, attemoted an allegori\ncal atory in hla picture of \"Hope,\" blind-J\nfolded and sitting upon a globe, holding a\nharp In her baida. The first impress loo\nupon- looking at this picture is that it\nshould hare been named \"Despair' rather\nthan \"Hod\" but the chief significance is\nan en dear or to show that while hope may\ncower in the darkness of a struggle, and\nher spirit may also be broken, there is still\none string which nerer quite snaps. This\nis the Hope of tbe World.\nQ. Who was the author of the- pbrane\n\"I was sired by the great American Eagle\nand foaled by a continental dam?\" H. JT.\nA. Mark Twain la tha \"Virginia City\nEnterprise.\"\nQ Where was tha first interurban car\nIn This country put In operation? K. C.\nI.\nA. The first Interurbat. car ia the Unit\ned States ran from Anderson, Indiana, 'to\nAlexandria, Indiana, January 1st, 1S96.\nQ. What is the true relation of, the north\nStar to the north pole?\nA. The north star reToIvea IB a circle\nabout 1 degrees in radius so that part\nof the time it is 1 degrees west of north\nand at times 1 degree east of north aud\nalso Is exactly on the meridian twice a\nday.\nQ. How do crabs breathe? B. E. M.\nA. As a rule, crabs breathe by gills,\nwhich are lodged In a pair of cavities at\nthe aides gf nie caraface, but in the true\nland-crabs, the cavities become enlarged\nand modified so as to act as lungs tor\nbreathing air.\nQ. What are a childs chances of recov\nery from diphtheria? D. P.\nA. It used to be that one child in rrerT\nthree that got diphtheria died. A few years\nago an antitoxin lor tne disease was dis\ncovered and when this Is pronerlv annlied\nbut one child in a hundred dies with the\nmalady. Our Washington Information\nBureau has a booklet on child health which\ntells how- to detect diphtheria and other\ncontagious diseases. It will send this\nbooklet frea to any one on receipts of a\ntwo cent stamp for return postage.\n(Any readex can get tn answer to any\n3u est ion by writing The Tooeka State\nournal information bureau. Frederic J.\nHaskin, Director. Washington, D. C. This\nofer applies strictly to Information. The\nbureau csnnot give advice on legal, medical,\nand financial matters. It does npt under\ntake to settle domestic troubles, nr to\nundertake exhaustive research on any\nsubject. Write your question plainly and\nbriefly. Give full name and address and\nencKfee S-cent eta nip for return pontage.\nAil replies ara asnt direct ta tha InaulreO\nJUST FOLKS\nBY EDGAR A. GUEST.\nsigns or i-aix.\nTrees all dressed in red an' brorn.\nGray skies hoverln over town, -Early\nmorniugs thick; with fog\nRising froin the distant bog,\nGrass so wet with falling dew\nThat your shoes get wet clear thru\nIf you walk across tbe lawn\nTo some bush with blossoms en,\nMartin boasts vacant now.\nAnd the wren house on the bough\nKmptv, too. Thee signs are all\nTelling Us that tt la Fall.\nCattle thru tha esrly day\nCloser to each other stay,\nKeepln' warm, an' riglit an left\nFields of all their wealth bereft\nWhere bnt yesterday was geld,\nNow Is brown and bleak and cold;\nIn the orchards all the trees\nSrm to stand an' take their ease.\nWe have claimed the fruit they bere.\nStripped them of their lnscions atora\nAnd each bnlging bin and stall v\nTells us plainly it is Fall.\nRosea that were proud and fay\nSeem to want to get away;\nLike a man who's borne the strain\nOt stern duty's bard campaign,\nAnd worn out by besvy deeds\nSeks the rent he sorely needs.\nSo the plants and vines appear\nTired and wan this time of year.\nJust as tho their ssrengtb was shrlvest\nI y the beauty they have giren;\nWritten large oa Nature's wall\now we read the signs f FalL\n(Copyright. VSJO, by Kdgar A- Guest.)\n1 J' 1 1\nEvening Story 1\nHospital Room Fourteen.\nBY WILL T. AMES.\nKiss McClintock, the business-like\nCanadian supervisor, found Nurse\nPadget coming; out of the diefkitchen\nwith -a breakfast tray destined for\nroom 14. \"Nurse,\" said the super\nvisor in her impersonal military man\nner, \"you are relieved.- Go.to the\ndormitory now and at 7 report to\nNight Supervisor Henry. Tou are to\ntake Nurse Boudette's place in the\nwomen s free ward; she is called home\nby the sudden illness of her mother. I\nwill take the tray who ia it for?\"\n\"Room 14. Very well, supervisor.\"\nSuperfluous conversation between\nnurses and superiors was discouraged\nin the hospital, particularly any dis\ncussion of explicit orders.! So Nurse\nPadget, surrendering the napkin\ncovered tray, marched like a soldier\ndewn the long corridor and -the long\nstairway and straight to her tiny room\nin the detached dormitory.\nEvelyn Padget was in the last year\nof her training course. As she sat at\nher window abstractedly gazing over\nthe city, spread, clean in the morning\nlight on three sides of Hospital Hill, it\noccurred to her that her new detail\ncarried with it something very like an\nhonor, for Maida Boudette was head\nnurse in the women's free ward, and a\ntwo-year graduate and never before\nsince Evelyn had been in the hospital\nhad a trainer been left in charge of\nany ward, even in an emergency.\n\"I suppose I ought to be grateful to\nold McClintock,\" soliloquized the girl.\nThen she proceeded to demonstrate\nher delight by doing something that\nthree-year trainers are supposed to be\nall thru -with she began to cry,\nquietly but earnestly.\nFor ten days- Nurse Padget had been\ntaking care of Hugh Morris, other\nwise and professionally designated as\nRoom Fourteen. Hugh had brought\nback from France mixed up with the\nmuscles of his neck a sliver of shrap\nnels Lately the sliver had been acting\nqueerly, and Morris's doctor had de\ncided that it had best come out of\nthat before it made serious trouble for\nthe ex-soldier's vertebrae. So there\nhad been an operation, with much\nsubsequent fussing with bandages, etc.,\nand with the collateral hunger for cod\ndling which every big boy marooned\non a bed of convalescence experiences.\nTen days is not long In the view\npoint of a geologist or of an anti\nquarian society. But in the St. Mi\nhiel salient, or in the life of a lad and\na lass, it can work stupendous\nchanges. Yesterday Room Fourteen\nhad said:\n\"Nurse, do you know whom you re\nmind me of? Well, it's my mother\nher picture when she was a girl.\" And\nhe had been very serious and earnest\nabout it, too. tho aa a matter of fact\nEvelyn resembled that long-gone\nmother not at all.\nEvelyn's heart had Jumped right up\ninto her throat when RomxFourteen\nsaid that, for the girl doesn't live who\ncan't analyze the meaning of this par\nticular compliment. She had laughed\nlightly and replied\ninn.. ,V,a,\nbutter? Well, you cah't iiave it un\nless the doctor says soiv\nAnd she got herself quickly out of\n,the room with the luncheon things\nbut in the long, deserted corridor she\nhastily kissed the corner, of the nap\nkin he had wiped his lips with.\nAnd now Room Fourteen would be\ngoing; out, certainly inside a week\nand what chance was there of Bou\ndotte's returning within that time?\nNone, of course. She would not be\nable to-.see him again. The rigid hos\npital discipline would prevent that\nand even if this were not so, how could\na self-respecting girl go throwing herj\nself in a patient's way without genu\nine reasons in the line of duty? If\nonly Malda Boudette's mother had\ntaken some other time to be ill?\nAt this thought Evelyn sat up very\nsuddenly and very straight. Jalda\nhad no mother! She was an orphan\nand herself had told Evelyn that she\nhad not been on speaking terms with\nher stepmother for two years. There\nwas something queer, then, about this\nsudden absentee of Nrse Boudette.\nNurse Padget's little head all at once\nbecame a perfect whirl of exciting\nspeculations, as the result of which,\nafter she had thought and thought till\nalmost noon, Evelyn took her courage\nin her hand and went to see the su-\ni-i. i jf\nAl X O C1UCK. Hi sh -n;,ii 1 1 L 1 11-1 wucu\na certain Mrs. Georgiana Boudette in\na neighboring state: \"Ia\"your Illness\nserious enough to require presence of\ndaughter?\" At 4- came this reply:\n\"Have no-daughter. Wouldn't let Ida\nB. touch me if I was dying.\"\nAt 4:0 Miss McClintock, stern and\ninquisitorial, sat in her office with\nNurse Halliburton, the prettiest girl of\nthe trailing personnel and th'e most\ntroublesome that had ever managed to\nremain for a third year In that insti\ntution. They had been closeted for\nfifteen minutes, and now Miss McClin\ntock was summing up. like a judge,!\nsight, and with your usual suscep\ntibility were, as your kind 'of a girl\ncalls it, 'crazy about him; that on\nthree different occasions you\" slighted\nyour own work and tried to induce\nNurse Padget tb let you substitute\ntemporarily for her so that ydu might\nbecome acquainted with this patient;\nthat Padget refused each time; that\non your mutual half .day out you and\nNurse Boudette discussed Nurse Pad\nget and your interest in room 14; that\nNurse Boudette declared she did not\nlike Nurse Padget because she was\ntoo fussy and straight-laced,\" and\nwould like to help you get her out of\nroom 14's service and get you in; that\nNurse Boudette finally announced that\nshe had long been determined on an\nextra vacation and that she imight as\nwell go now as later, inasmuch as\nthere was a shortage of graduate\nnurses and Nurse Padget would be\nsure to be assigned to her place in the\nwomen's free and the regular routine\nof assignments would give you room\n14 and the rest of Padget's patients.\nHave I stated the case correctly?\"\nTearfully a vVy penitent trainer ad\nmitted the truth of the indictment.\n\"Very well. Go to the dormitory. 1\nwill submit your case to the superin\ntendnl. Ask Nurge Padget to come to\nme, please.\"\nMiss McClintock was military and\nbusiness like and could, be cold and\nstem, but she had a magnificent sense\nof justice. To Evefc-n she said:\n\"Your surmise was correct, nurse.\nConspiracies among the personnel can\nnot be permitted to regulate the course\nof events In this institution. xFor that\nreason -you will resume yourx former\ndetail at once. Other arrangements\nwill be made for the Women's Free.\"\nNurse Boadette's week off was 11\niimitably extended, so far as that hos\npital was concerned. Nurse Hallibur\nton's half days off were spent within\nthe Institution's limits for the rest of\nher training service and she regarded\nherself as a lucky girl.\nAnd as for Nurse Padget and Room\nFourteen why. what In the perfectly\nnatural, nninterfered with order of\nevents would occur to a man who sol-\nemnly compared a little, rather snub-\nnosed brunette to a stately, aquiline\nblonde mother... finding them alike\nand a girl who secretly kissed the nap\nkin his lips had touched? If there is\nany scintilla of doubt, hi it known\nthat the wedding announcements bore\nthe date of the day following; that\nyear's nurses' graduation.\n(Copyrisbt. 1920, by the McClure News\npiper Byndicste.1\nJUST A GIRL\n,BU JANE PHELPS\nTHE MARRIAGE QTJESTIOJr.\nCHAPTER 111.\nI used to wonder if I had remained\nin New Tort, If I had been near my\nold '.friends, if because of Claudia\nBhephard I would have seen Kenneth\nLawrence again. Altho they Were\ncousins I never remembered his hav\ning visited then but that once, but I\nhad often heard Claudia talk of him.\nSome way, when I was settled in my\nnew home with Mary and Tom, I\nthought more often of Kenneth. It\nmight have been because I saw how\nhappy and contented they were,\"altho\nthey worked hard. Tom was so kind\nand thoughtful, Mary so loving, that\nat times a lonely feeling clutched my\nheart, and I felt as if I, alone of all\nthe world, hadno one to eare.for me,\nMv work was going well. I tried in\nevery way to familiarize myself with\n,hB of tn. bond apartment.\nand had succeeded to the extent that\nnow I had nractically been made as\nsistant to the manager. Naturally I\nwas nleased. and a litte proud\n\"No girl \"who wasn't educated could\ndo what you've done.\" Mary said when\nwe talked about my rapid advance\nment. \"No girl could have done It even if\nshe was educated if she didn't work\nhard,\" said practical Tom. \"Miss Zena\nhas worked very hard, and deserves\nall the good luck that can come to\nher. But if you won't mind 1 want\nto sav something, can I\n\"Of course you may Tom! anything\nvou like.\" I replied heartily. X liKea\nThomas Clancy. I also respected him\nand his ODimons.\n\"I hardly know how to say it. Miss\nZena, but don't think that business,\nworking in an office, is everything\nthere is. Mary and I are so happy\ntogether so different from what we\nwere when we were working alone,\nthat I .we want you to be happy\ntoo, in the same Way. You ought to\nget married. Miss Zena. You aln t tne\nkind to go on working all your life.\nYou ought to \"have a home of -your\nown.\"\n\"My what a long speech for you,\nTom,\" I laughed. \"I sometimes am\na bit Jealous of you and Mary,\" I\nadded more seriously, \"but not for\nlong. I have to care for mother you\nknow. I am thinking constantly that\nin another year I may have her with\nme. Then I will have a home of my\nown. Altho to tell the truth I am\nvery contented here with you and\nMary.\"\n\"That ain't the idea. Miss Zena. vlt\nain't right that you shouldn't make\nsome nice man happy, and be happy\nwith him. I guess I'm old-fastU6ned,\nbut I think all nice girls, like you and\nMary, are sort of wasted unless, you\nget married. There's so many of the\nother kind that marry, the kind that\ndon't know how to be wives or how\nto help a man be a good husband, and\na successful man, that it seems a pity\nLnot to have all of your kind marry.\"\n1 was surprised to near xom taiK\nlike this. He was usually quiet, and\nsaid what he had to say in a few\nwords.\n\"I don't say I sha'n't marry, Tom.\nBut I have yet to meet the man\" I\nstopped, and felt the hot blood r,ush to\nmy face. I had met a man he was\nstill enshrined in my heart altho I had\nno way of knowing that he oared for\nme any longer. And I also knew that\nit was this feeling for Kenneth Law\nrence that had made me refuse to lis\nten to Tony Celand when everything\nwithin me cried out for the comfort\nand ease from work and responsibility\nhe. could give me; for what I could do\nfor mother as his wife.\n\"If you haven't, you'll meet him\nsome day. Miss Zena. Don't have your\nmind so full of your work that you\nwon't realize he is the right man.\"\n\"Oh, Zena won't b-i Miss Stewart-always!\"\nMary broke in. \"You two are\ntoo serious. I lieard a little bird say\nthat she could get-married any time\nshe wanted and to- a. fine man, too.\n\"Little birds sometimes gossiD when\nt,\nthey have no reason to. Mary. Don't\nJisten to them,\" I replied laughingly.\nThen: \"If you two say anything more\nabout my getting married I shall think\nyou are tired of me; that you want to\nget rid of me.\"\n\"Oh, Miss Zena!\" and \"Oh, Zena!\"\nthey exclaimed in-chorus, and the sub\nject was dropped. But I often thought\nof Tom's homely advice; his odd way\nof putting his thougiits 6f matrimony\ninto words\n\"All nice girls like you and Mary\nare sort of wasted unless you get mar\nried, was ne right?\n(Tomorrow A proposal)\nLITTLE BENNY'S NOTE BOOK\nBY IiEFJ PAPE.\nPop was smoaking with his feet up\nand I was setting on the floor looking\nat the advertisements in the paper to\nkeep my mind off my homewerk, and\nI saw one saying. Be a Draftsman-\nEarn Good Money With Little Werk.\nMe thinking, G..I wonder wst a\ndraftsman is?- I bet its a man that\ngoes erround putting windows up and\ndown for millionairs so they will get\nenuff air without getting in too big of\na draft.\nSounding likea good easy job .with\nout needing mutch study or ixperience,\nand I started to practice ,on pop\nwaking erround the room and opening\nall the windows about 6 inches and\nthen I wawked erround agen and\nopened them about 4 more -inches and\nthen put them all down agen about 2\ninehes on account of the air starting\nto come in too fast, wtch Jest then pop\ngave a fearse sneeze, saying. Confound\nit, I jest got rid of one cold and heer\nI am sneezing agen.\nMe thinking, Holey smoaksi-draftsman\nto the rescue.\nAnd I quick started to goxerfsrfnd\nputting all the windows down agen.\nand pop sneezed 4 more sneezes with\nout stopping, saying. Wat in the name\nof ventilatiori are you doing with those\nWindows?\nfir? Im putting them down, I sed.\nand pop sc-d. Putting tame down, well\nwho and wy aniven were they put\nup?\nSir? I put them up to practice be\ning a draftsman and earn good money\nwith little werk, I sed.\nYoure the ony one In the werld\nknews wat youre tawking about, shut\nthose windows; aed pop.\nC. pop, thats wat Im doingvf sed.\nWich I was and poivkepp on snecfeinK,\nand sed, young man. youll rue this day.\nvvell G, pop, gosh, wat is a drafts\nman? Shut up, sed pop.\nWich I did, and pop kepp en sneez-\nitft.\nON SECOND THOUGHT\nBY JAY E. HOUSB.\n(Froa Falladtlpala PabOc Ledge.)\nYou may recallXhe firm ut gentle\nmanner in whicht'ornelius Vanderbilt,\njr., once reproved the column. Corne\nlius, Jr.. took slight umbrage at our\nraillery, and announced Hie intention\nof returning to his beloved newspaper\nwork the moment his three weeks'\nleave ef absence had expired.\n7 -This\nmerely Is to note that Cornelius\nkept his word. He is back in news\npaper work, threading the waning\nmonths of his honeymoon with honest\ntoil. And last week he wrote: \"Four\nteen years ago San Francisco passed\ntnru the lowest pinnacle of her an\nnals.\" s\nThey are paying young Mr. Vander\nbilt $1!5 a week for that sort of thing.\nWe have been fired for less. The poor\nman has no chance.\n'What,\" writes amanxious inquirert\n'is' the best method for having nine\nteeth extracted for a young man thir- I\nty-two years old who has hed a heart\ntnurinur since he was twenty-one?\"\nWe hesitate to predicate aflvica uncn\na superficial diagnosis, but if, in addi\ntion, the young man drives a Henry\ncar-.wlth a broken windshield, has his\nwinter's coal in and is not susceptible\nto hay fever at an elevation of 1,000\nfeet, he should have them pulled.\nThe use of dynamite in such cases is\nneither Indicated nor recommended.\nThe publicity which oozes from the\nfecund typewriters of the (correspond\nents at Marion, continues to engross\nour idle moments. Most of It is poor\nstuff, a turbid stream of banal per\nsonalities flowing slowly between low\nbanks of bunk. But. once in'a while,\nthere gleams from the breast of the\ncurrent a Jewel which lights the pro\ncesses of thought.\nWe sighted one such in the Sunday\npapers, it seems the Marion folk call\nMrs. Harding \"Florence.\" It is given\nonly to the exceptional woman to write\nher Christian name upon the con\nsciousness or ner community.\nWe grant the liberty of wide diverg\nence nt nnininn iinnn Va ma.li. r 1,\ncandidate himself. But we'd shoot our\nattenuated roll at 8 to 3 upon the\n(iiiiiViuuii ma mrs- xaaraing is all\nright. They wouldn't call her \"Flor\nence\" If she wasn't.\nWin t\"Vimv in liTfl. Cn..' A l.\nn,,,.\nSir On North Thi?3 street I lamped\nuna ajgn\n\"A Nickl Brush Mfg.\"\nAnd in the seven hundred block on\nNorth Seventh street there is a\n\"Rum1 For Rent.\"\nOn South Eighth street one says:\n\"Max Wasa Mfg. Jeweler.\" x\nWhat is he now? WIN.\nJ. C. S. wants us tb give our author-\nunLy ior \"Desiaes-- in the phrase, \"be\nsides his work as a controversialist.'\nThere ia aa w tiavo i ji\nt.i muiiiica,\nno authority for any phraseological\nvpuucu in inw column, wnen we\nneed a word \"we take one. If it hap\npens to be the correct word, so much\nthe better.\nWe know nettling as to the measure\nof Mr.-, Harding's statesmanship, but\nwe credit him with one considerable\naccomplishment. He haa kept the\nNew York Tribune, which emerged\nfrom the Chi\nrymal mood, from fretting Itself sick\"\nWe are not disposed to cavil because\nGovernor Cox's newspaper was strok\ning Germany with a velvet -glove as\nlate as 11, We fought the war In\na limited way andwe recall that a\ngreat many of the patriots hadito have\nthe benefit of artificial stimulus.\nA I gentleman named Whiting, who\ntook off his white collar and went into\nthe works for a number of months,\nwhere labored under the cover of\nanonymity, haS written a book in\nwhich he interprets the worker's mind.\nIt is praiseworthy endeavor, but the\nthing cannot be done in that way.\nThe only person competent td re\nveal the. worker's mind Is one who,\nwith the average worker's intellect,\nemerges from a background of pov\nerty and toil to take up a worker's life\nand follow it. And the chances are\nhe Couldn't write a book about it in\na thousand years.\nThe rrouble is that those capable\nof writing of the underside of tife\nmust ge its color vicariously.\nThere are various ways of wasting\ntime. One of them is to spend itcol\noring a meerschaum pipe.\nA man has a little Something \"on\"\nMusic Is Esszntim-vf-'my\"\nc5TjND THE TESTS' TltlE\nWhen we sell a Vose Piano\nwe do not GUESS about the\nservice it is going to render.\nFor years we have sold\nthese remarkable Pianos\nand we KNOW what every one will do. The outstanding\ncharacteristic of the Vose is its\nonderf ul Durability\nVose tone is rich and sireet after years of use and Vose action\nstill responsive because of this characteristic. Ask any Vose\nowner.\n'Our Prices' the Lowest\nLet us show you how\neasy you can \"own\" be--cause\nof the Jenkins plan.\nCall or write today.\n833\na woman when It comes t packing\nueroj.n in buhvaw.\nEvery married man hag' TieOTtl'Tita\nwife say,. \"I didn't marry your fam\nily.\" And some of them have heard\nit many times.\nWhat tiA hppnniH nt thM old- rash\nloned sport whose idea of a celebration\nwas to hire at hack ana riae arouna\ntown with top down?\n1\nDorothy Dix Talks\nBt DO BOTHY DIX\nWeatra Blghee M Wesu\nTho Economy (piliop 1.\nWhen many a woman dies and goes\nup before the judgment bar, she la\ngoing to be condemned because she\nhas sinned the sin of the attic and in\nthe particular hell to which she is as\nsigned she will be tormented by the\nimps of the things that she haa sel\nishly and senselessly hoarded.\nShe will be stamped upon, and\nwalked upon, and kicked about by\nthe shoes that she has let moulder\nand rot while the feet of her neigh\nbors were bare upon the ground.\nShe is going to be smothered under\nJhe mattresses that she let decay while\ntne old women turned tneir wary oia\nbodtes at night on hard beds.\nShe is going to be pinched by tha\nbed springs that ehe let rust out while\nher laundress had1 nothing but a hard\nboard ,to lie on.\nShe is going to go naked and shiver\ning in the bitter cold while the stacks\nof warm dresses and overcoats, and\nCloaks that ehe let go to decay grin\nat her and mock- her with their\nwarmth.\nIn her ears she will hear ceaselessly\nthe wail of new-born babes without a\nrag to cover them while trunks full\nof the little clothea -of her own chil\ndren slowly fall into dust- before her\neyes.\nShe will be haunted by the wistful\nfaces olj little children who reach out\neager hands for the toys that only\nthe rata playedWith in -her garret.\nAnd after aeons of, years ot this\ntorture perhaps the woman who has\nsinned1 the sin of the attic will have\nexpiated -her crime, and get another\nchance at life. Perhaps it was a wo\nman who sinned the sin of the attic\nin some previous incarnation who\ndevised the scheme that she calls the\nEconomy Shop, which is a sort of\ndouble-barreled philanthropy that hits\nboth the attic and the high cost of\nliving.\nThat I dw not know, but I do know\nthat the Sconomy Shop is one of the\ncleverest, most practical and efficient\nways of solving a number of prob\nlems that has ever been devised.\nThe woman with the Economy Shop\nIdea lives In a little mid-western town\nof about thirty thousand Inhabitants.\nShe is rich and socially important, and\npossessed of great executive ability, and\nshe put her big scheme into operation\nby taking a small storehouse, and in\nviting a certain nurnber of girls to\ncome and be clerks for her, and ask\ning all her friends to send into the\nstorehouse anything that they had\nthajt they didn't want, from a white\nelephant to a peck of potatoes.\n(CopjrlgbtxlOM, by the Wheeler Erndicata\ny. Inc.)\nGeorge Matthew Adams\nDaily Talk\nTHE WINDbws OF. tiiOVR MIND.\npJhe mind Is continually la a state of\nlight or darkjiess. It has windows!\nAnd each window is equipped with\ncurtains. Some people keep these\ncurtains drawn most of the time so\nthat they see little of the beauty of\nthe world. Others lift their shades\nonly during storms and when darkness\nhovers about.\nBut the one who sees in life some\nthing that is well worth while, keeps\nhis windows in an ever inviting mood\nfor the sun and light.\nSo that in darkness, during Storms\nand stress, such a mind may reflect\nand in so doing highly resolve to keep\nbrave and calm and cool in spirit till\nthe clouds and rain roll past and the\nlight streams in! 4\nKeep the windows of your mind\never open ready -for the angels of\ncheer to fly in.\nA well conducted business always\npays dividends. So does a well or\ndered mind not quarterly, but daily!\nLook out of the windows of your\nmind. Watch the world as it passes\nby. Toss to it your sympathy and\nlove. Be co-operative. There are far\nmore good days withsun and happi-'\nnss than dark ones with little \"blue\ndevils\" on parade.\nSavCsrlOsicQ).\nKansas Ave. Phone 4208\nsliBll\nV 3","height":"23552","width":"21756"}}
